  "text": "The Rust compiler's trait obligation chain follows a sophisticated flow for resolving trait bounds:\n\n## Core Data Structure: ObligationForest\nThe foundational data structure is `ObligationForest<O>` (compiler/rustc_data_structures/src/obligation_forest/mod.rs), which manages outstanding trait obligations. It uses a tree-based approach where each obligation can spawn sub-obligations. The forest processes obligations by invoking an `ObligationProcessor` callback that returns `ProcessResult` (either `Unchanged`, `Changed(sub_obligations)`, or `Error`).\n\n## Fulfillment Engine\n`FulfillmentContext<'tcx, E>` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/fulfill.rs) acts as the top-level engine coordinating trait resolution. It:\n1. Wraps an `ObligationForest<PendingPredicateObligation<'tcx>>`\n2. Implements the `FulfillProcessor` to handle obligation processing\n3. Calls `process_trait_obligation` for trait predicates, invoking `SelectionContext::select()` to check solvability\n4. Returns `ProcessResult::Changed(subobligations)` when selection succeeds with additional subgoals\n\n## Candidate Selection\n`SelectionContext<'cx, 'tcx>` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/mod.rs) is the core selection engine that:\n1. Invokes `assemble_candidates()` (from candidate_assembly.rs) to collect all candidate implementations\n2. Evaluates each candidate through `eval_candidate()`\n3. Confirms the best candidate via `confirm_candidate()` (confirmation.rs)\n4. Returns a `Selection` containing the proof that the trait is satisfied\n\n## Candidate Assembly\n`SelectionContext::assemble_candidates()` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/candidate_assembly.rs) performs the crucial candidate collection step by:\n1. Assembling candidates from trait aliases\n2. Assembling candidates from user-defined impls via `assemble_candidates_from_impls()`\n3. Assembling candidates from caller bounds (where clauses)\n4. Assembling builtin candidates for traits like Copy, Clone, Sized\n5. Handling special lang items and auto traits\n\n## Impl Matching\n`MatchAgainstFreshVars` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/_match.rs) handles the crucial impl matching logic. It:\n1. Matches impl trait references against fresh type variables\n2. Uses type relation machinery to check if an impl could satisfy a trait obligation\n3. Provides the pattern matching mechanism for determining if \"fresh types in B could be instantiated with values to make it equal to A\"\n4. Returns Ok/Err based on whether unification is possible\n\n## Candidate Confirmation\n`SelectionContext::confirm_candidate()` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/traits/select/confirmation.rs) confirms that a selected candidate actually works by:\n1. Normalizing trait references\n2. Unifying impl types with the obligation's types\n3. Generating subobligations for where-clause predicates\n4. Returning the confirmed `Selection` with all subobligations\n\n## Error Reporting\nWhen obligations cannot be satisfied, error reporting occurs in two stages:\n1. `report_fulfillment_errors()` (compiler/rustc_trait_selection/src/error_reporting/traits/mod.rs) - Organizes and deduplicates fulfillment errors\n2. `fulfillment_errors.rs` - Provides detailed error messages for unsatisfied trait bounds, including suggestions and context\n\nThe complete chain works as: FulfillmentContext registers obligations → ObligationForest processes them → FulfillProcessor drives SelectionContext → assemble_candidates collects candidates → MatchAgainstFreshVars filters via impl matching → confirm_candidate generates subobligations → cycle repeats until all obligations satisfied or errors reported."
